  "elapsed_s": 2.5,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 13,
      "text": "And, in fact, the Jewish man who owned that factory or was the son of the owners had been educated in Germany in textile fabrication and design, and knew the German, by coincidence, who was assigned to take over that factory.",
      "word_count": 41
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 14,
      "text": "A man by the name of Schultz was the German.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 15,
      "text": "And our friend, his name was Rowinski, R-O-W-I-N-S-K-I.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 16,
      "text": "And my father was a doctor in that factory.",
      "word_count": 9
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 17,
      "text": "So from our apartment, he went every morning with his papers to the factory, worked there all day, came back in the evening.",
      "word_count": 23
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 18,
      "text": "Very soon after the-- we called it actions and later on selections started.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 19,
      "text": "People were not willing to go-- to go willingly, [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] partly because they-- they were unsure of what happened there, and partly because the news started to filter back that there was something wrong with this whole project.",
      "word_count": 41
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 20,
      "text": "The trains which were supposed to go deep into Russia, the same trains were coming back in the evening of the day on which they were sent.",
      "word_count": 27
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 21,
      "text": "You know, the people who-- the Jews who worked at the siding from which the trains left, the place called Umschlagplatz-- and I'm not sure I know the translation of the word 'umschlag,' but it was-- 'platz' means, of course, 'place,' 'starting place,' or something, 'loading place,' something like that, the siding which was in the ghetto from which the trains left.",
      "word_count": 62
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 22,
      "text": "The people who worked there-- there were some Jews who worked on loading the trains and then maintaining that little facility there, which had an infirmary and a waiting place, and so on, some buildings, they begin to notice that the trains came back the same day, meaning that, of course, they couldn't have gone very far.",
      "word_count": 57
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 7,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 23,
      "text": "And the trains were loaded absolutely to the gills.",
      "word_count": 9
    }
  ],
